      <content>Key definitions: Incident triage (rapid assessment/prioritization of alerts); Security incident (violation/threat to policies); Alert (notification of potential event); False positive (incorrect incident alert); True positive (valid incident); Severity/priority (classification by CIA impact).</content>
    </layer>
    <layer level="2" name="Layer 2">
      <focus/>
      <content>Core components of triage workflow: Intake (receive alerts from SIEM/tools); Validation (confirm true/false positive via log checks, correlation); Prioritization (score using factors: impact on confidentiality/integrity/availability, urgency, scope); Frameworks: NIST SP 800-61 Rev. 3 (Detect phase integration with CSF 2.0).</content>
    </layer>
    <layer level="3" name="Layer 3">
      <focus/>
      <content>Step-by-step process: 1) Intake alert; 2) Validate (check credibility, correlate indicators); 3) Score severity (matrix: e.g., high impact + high urgency = critical); 4) Escalate/assign (e.g., low to Tier 1, critical to Tier 3). Best practices: Use tools (SIEM like Splunk), reduce false positives via tuning, document decisions.</content>
    </layer>
    <layer level="4" name="Layer 4">
      <focus/>
      <content>Integrate with full IR lifecycle (NIST: Detect → Triage → Respond/Recover); Team roles (Tier 1 analysts triage, escalate to Tier 2/3); Optimization (metrics: triage time &lt;15 min, false positive rate &lt;20%); Link to broader IR team organization and forensics.</content>
    </layer>
